            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "hard", q: "A chain of amino acids that folds into a specific 3-D shape is called a:", options: ["Polysaccharide", "Polypeptide / protein", "Triglyceride", "Polynucleotide"], answer: 1, explanation: "A polypeptide is a chain of amino acids; when it folds into a working 3-D shape it becomes a functional protein." },
            { type: "long", difficulty: "hard", q: "Compare the monomer units and biological roles of carbohydrates and proteins, using one example of each.", answer: "Carbohydrates are built from monosaccharide monomers (e.g. glucose). They mainly provide energy — glucose is used in cellular respiration and starch is an energy store in plants. Proteins are built from amino acid monomers. They have many roles: enzymes speed up chemical reactions, structural proteins like collagen support tissues, and haemoglobin carries oxygen. Both are polymers, but their different monomers give them very different properties and roles.", explanation: "Monomers differ; carbs = energy, proteins = structural and functional roles." }
