            { type: "tf", difficulty: "medium", q: "Fats (lipids) also help insulate the body and protect internal organs as well as store energy.", answer: true, explanation: "Lipids have multiple structural and functional roles beyond just energy storage." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "medium", q: "The phospholipid bilayer of the cell membrane is made mainly of:", options: ["Carbohydrate", "Nucleic acid", "Lipid", "Pure protein"], answer: 2, explanation: "Phospholipids (a type of lipid) form the two-layered membrane around every cell." },
            { type: "match", difficulty: "medium", q: "Match each biomolecule to its function.", pairs: [["Carbohydrate","Quick energy supply"],["Protein","Enzyme and structural roles"],["Lipid","Long-term energy and insulation"],["Nucleic acid","Genetic information storage"]], explanation: "Each biomolecule's structure suits a specific set of body functions." },
            { type: "short", difficulty: "medium", q: "Why does the cell membrane need to be flexible and selectively permeable?", answer: "The cell membrane controls what enters and leaves the cell. It must be flexible to allow cell shape changes, and it contains protein channels and carriers that let some substances (like glucose) in while blocking others. The lipid bilayer blocks most water-soluble molecules, while protein channels provide selective entry.", explanation: "Lipid bilayer = flexible barrier; proteins = selective gates." },
            { type: "short", difficulty: "hard", q: "Explain why the precise folded shape of a protein matters for an enzyme.", answer: "An enzyme's chain of amino acids folds into a specific 3-D shape that includes an active site. The active site fits its substrate like a lock and key. If the shape changes (e.g. by heat or wrong pH), the active site no longer fits and the enzyme cannot work — so structure directly determines function.", explanation: "Shape makes the active site; the right shape lets the enzyme bind its substrate." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "hard", q: "Haemoglobin is a protein in red blood cells that carries oxygen. This is an example of:", options: ["A structural function of protein", "An enzymatic function of protein", "A transport function of protein", "A genetic function of protein"], answer: 2, explanation: "Haemoglobin transports oxygen in the blood — a transport function of proteins." },
            { type: "long", difficulty: "hard", q: "Explain how the structure of a lipid molecule relates to its role as a long-term energy store, and compare this to how carbohydrates function as a short-term energy source.", answer: "Lipid molecules (triglycerides) contain long hydrocarbon chains in their fatty acid tails. These chains are rich in C-H bonds that release a large amount of energy when broken during respiration — about 38 kJ/g compared to 17 kJ/g for carbohydrates. Lipids are also hydrophobic, so they do not attract water and are stored in a compact, concentrated form. Carbohydrates (e.g. glycogen) are soluble, can be broken down quickly, and are readily available for immediate energy needs. Lipids store more energy per gram but take longer to mobilise, making them better for long-term storage while carbohydrates fuel rapid activity.", explanation: "Lipids = dense, long-term energy; carbs = quick, accessible energy." }
