            { type: "tf", difficulty: "easy", q: "Vitamins and minerals are micronutrients, needed only in small amounts.", answer: true, explanation: "We need them in tiny quantities, but they are still essential." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "easy", q: "Which of these is a macronutrient?", options: ["Vitamin C", "Iron", "Carbohydrate", "Calcium"], answer: 2, explanation: "Carbohydrates, proteins and fats are macronutrients (needed in large amounts); vitamins and minerals are micronutrients." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "easy", q: "The three macronutrients are:", options: ["Vitamins, minerals, water", "Carbohydrates, proteins, fats", "Fibre, calcium, iron", "Glucose, amino acids, nucleotides"], answer: 1, explanation: "Carbohydrates, proteins and fats are needed in large amounts as macronutrients." },
            { type: "tf", difficulty: "easy", q: "Water is not a nutrient because it provides no energy.", answer: false, explanation: "Water is an essential nutrient even though it provides no energy; it is needed for all body reactions and transport." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "medium", q: "Which mineral is essential for making haemoglobin in red blood cells?", options: ["Calcium", "Iron", "Fluoride", "Phosphorus"], answer: 1, explanation: "Iron is needed to form haemoglobin, the protein that carries oxygen in the blood." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "medium", q: "Vitamin D helps the body to:", options: ["Fight infection", "Absorb calcium for strong bones and teeth", "Speed up digestion", "Carry oxygen"], answer: 1, explanation: "Vitamin D promotes calcium absorption in the gut, essential for bone and teeth development." },
            { type: "match", difficulty: "medium", q: "Match each nutrient type to its main role.", pairs: [["Carbohydrate","Energy supply"],["Protein","Growth and repair"],["Fat","Long-term energy and insulation"],["Minerals","Specific chemical processes (e.g. iron for blood)"]], explanation: "Each nutrient class has a distinct primary function in the body." },
            { type: "tf", difficulty: "medium", q: "Fibre (dietary roughage) is classed as a macronutrient even though it cannot be digested.", answer: false, explanation: "Fibre is not a macronutrient in the energy-providing sense; it is a carbohydrate that the body cannot digest but it aids gut movement (peristalsis)." },
            { type: "short", difficulty: "medium", q: "Give two differences between macronutrients and micronutrients.", answer: "1. Amount needed: macronutrients are required in large quantities (grams per day); micronutrients are needed in tiny amounts (milligrams or micrograms). 2. Role: macronutrients provide energy and the raw materials for growth; micronutrients do not provide energy but are essential for specific chemical reactions and body processes.", explanation: "Amount required and energy-provision role distinguish macro from micro." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "hard", q: "A diet can be 'adequate in calories' yet still be nutritionally deficient. This is called:", options: ["Starvation", "Hidden hunger (micronutrient deficiency)", "Obesity", "Kwashiorkor"], answer: 1, explanation: "Hidden hunger means enough food energy but too little of key vitamins or minerals, leading to deficiency diseases." },
            { type: "long", difficulty: "hard", q: "Explain why a growing 12-year-old needs more calcium and protein than a 40-year-old adult of the same body mass.", answer: "During growth, bones are lengthening and increasing in density, which requires large amounts of calcium. A 12-year-old is also building new muscle mass and other body tissues, requiring more protein for growth and cell production. In contrast, a 40-year-old mainly uses protein for maintenance and repair of existing tissues, and bones are no longer growing. Hormonal growth signals in adolescence also increase the rate of protein synthesis. Therefore, the nutrient requirements relative to body mass are higher during growth.", explanation: "Growth demands more calcium (bones) and protein (tissue building) than maintenance does." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "hard", q: "Which statement correctly distinguishes macronutrients from micronutrients?", options: ["Macronutrients contain carbon; micronutrients do not", "Macronutrients are needed in large amounts and provide energy or building materials; micronutrients are needed in tiny amounts for specific body processes", "Micronutrients include carbohydrates and fats", "Macronutrients include vitamins and minerals"], answer: 1, explanation: "The defining differences are quantity required and function: macronutrients in grams for energy/structure; micronutrients in milligrams or less for regulatory processes." }
