            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "medium", q: "Goitre is an enlargement of the thyroid gland caused by lack of:", options: ["Iron", "Iodine", "Calcium", "Vitamin D"], answer: 1, explanation: "Iodine is needed to make thyroid hormones; deficiency leads to goitre (swollen thyroid)." },
            { type: "tf", difficulty: "easy", q: "Night blindness can result from a deficiency of vitamin A.", answer: true, explanation: "Vitamin A is needed to make visual pigments; deficiency causes poor vision in dim light (night blindness)." },
            { type: "match", difficulty: "medium", q: "Match each deficiency disease to its missing nutrient.", pairs: [["Scurvy","Vitamin C"],["Rickets","Vitamin D / calcium"],["Anaemia","Iron"],["Goitre","Iodine"]], explanation: "Each deficiency disease has a specific nutrient that is lacking." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "medium", q: "Kwashiorkor is a disease of children in which the abdomen swells. It is caused by a lack of:", options: ["Carbohydrate", "Vitamin B", "Protein", "Fat"], answer: 2, explanation: "Kwashiorkor results from severe protein deficiency; marasmus results from overall calorie/energy deficit." },
            { type: "tf", difficulty: "medium", q: "Deficiency diseases can usually be cured or prevented by including the missing nutrient in the diet.", answer: true, explanation: "Most deficiency diseases reverse once the missing nutrient is restored, e.g. vitamin C cures scurvy." },
            { type: "short", difficulty: "medium", q: "Why are children in developing countries particularly at risk of vitamin A deficiency?", answer: "Vitamin A is found mainly in animal products (liver, dairy, eggs) and colourful fruits/vegetables. In regions where diets lack variety and are heavily based on staple grains, these foods may be too expensive or unavailable. Children need more vitamin A relative to their body size for growth and immune function, so deficiency can develop faster than in adults.", explanation: "Limited food variety + higher growth needs make children vulnerable to deficiency." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "hard", q: "Adding iodine to table salt is an example of:", options: ["A food test", "Food fortification to prevent deficiency disease", "A food preservative", "A flavour enhancer"], answer: 1, explanation: "Food fortification adds micronutrients (like iodine) to commonly eaten foods to prevent deficiency at a population level." },
            { type: "long", difficulty: "hard", q: "Explain how iron deficiency causes anaemia, and describe two strategies that could reduce its prevalence in a low-income community.", answer: "Iron is needed to make haemoglobin, the protein in red blood cells that carries oxygen. When iron is deficient, fewer or smaller red blood cells are produced, so less oxygen reaches the body's cells. The person feels tired, pale and breathless — this is anaemia. Two strategies: (1) Food fortification — add iron to widely consumed staple foods like flour or rice, ensuring the whole community gets more iron without needing to change food habits. (2) Nutrition education — teach families to eat iron-rich foods (beans, leafy greens, meat) and to eat them with vitamin-C-rich foods (citrus, tomatoes) which enhance iron absorption.", explanation: "Iron needed for haemoglobin; less iron = less oxygen carried; fortification and education are prevention strategies." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "hard", q: "Beriberi is a neurological disease caused by a deficiency of vitamin B1 (thiamine). Which food staple, when eaten in excess without variety, is most associated with beriberi?", options: ["Wholegrain wheat", "Polished white rice", "Fresh vegetables", "Legumes (beans and lentils)"], answer: 1, explanation: "Polishing rice removes the husk where thiamine is concentrated; populations relying on white rice without variety are at high risk of beriberi." }
