          quiz: [
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "easy", q: "Air is best classified as a:", options: ["Element", "Compound", "Mixture", "Pure substance"], answer: 2, explanation: "Air is a mixture of gases (nitrogen, oxygen and others) not chemically bonded together." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "easy", q: "Table salt (sodium chloride, NaCl) is a:", options: ["Element", "Mixture", "Compound", "Colloid"], answer: 2, explanation: "Sodium chloride contains sodium and chlorine chemically bonded in a 1:1 ratio — it is a compound." },
            { type: "tf", difficulty: "easy", q: "A mixture can be separated by physical methods without a chemical reaction.", answer: true, explanation: "Physical methods (filtration, distillation, etc.) separate mixtures; a chemical reaction would be needed to break a compound apart." },
            { type: "short", difficulty: "hard", q: "Explain the difference between a compound and a mixture, with one example of each.", answer: "In a compound, different elements are chemically bonded in fixed proportions and can only be separated by a chemical reaction (e.g. water, H2O). In a mixture, substances are just physically combined in any proportion and can be separated by physical methods (e.g. salty water or air). A compound has new properties; a mixture keeps the properties of its parts.", explanation: "Compound = chemically bonded, fixed ratio; mixture = physically combined, separable physically." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "medium", q: "Copper sulfate (CuSO4) is formed when copper, sulfur and oxygen are chemically combined. It is a:", options: ["Mixture", "Element", "Compound", "Colloid"], answer: 2, explanation: "Copper sulfate contains more than one element chemically bonded together — it is a compound." },
            { type: "match", difficulty: "medium", q: "Classify each substance as element, compound or mixture.", pairs: [["Pure gold","Element"],["Carbon dioxide (CO2)","Compound"],["Seawater","Mixture"],["Oxygen gas (O2)","Element"]], explanation: "Elements have one atom type; compounds have chemically bonded different atoms; mixtures are physically combined." },
            { type: "tf", difficulty: "medium", q: "A compound always contains atoms of two or more different elements.", answer: true, explanation: "By definition a compound is formed from two or more elements chemically joined, e.g. H2O, CO2, NaCl." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "medium", q: "Which method would separate iron filings from sand?", options: ["Filtration", "Distillation", "A magnet", "Crystallisation"], answer: 2, explanation: "Iron is magnetic; passing a magnet through the mixture picks out the iron filings, leaving the sand." },
            { type: "short", difficulty: "medium", q: "Classify these substances and justify your answers: pure water, crude oil, gold, salt dissolved in water.", answer: "Pure water (H2O) — compound (hydrogen and oxygen chemically bonded). Crude oil — mixture (many different hydrocarbons physically combined). Gold — element (only gold atoms). Salt dissolved in water (salt water) — mixture (salt and water not chemically bonded; can be separated by evaporation).", explanation: "Water = compound; crude oil = mixture; gold = element; salt water = mixture." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "hard", q: "Brass is an alloy of copper and zinc. An alloy is best classified as a:", options: ["Compound", "Element", "Mixture", "Pure substance"], answer: 2, explanation: "An alloy is a mixture of metals (or a metal with a non-metal); the components are not chemically bonded and retain variable proportions." },
            { type: "long", difficulty: "hard", q: "A student claims that water is a mixture because it contains hydrogen and oxygen. Explain why the student is incorrect, using evidence from the properties and composition of water to support your answer.", answer: "The student is wrong because water is a compound, not a mixture. Evidence: (1) Water always contains hydrogen and oxygen in the exact fixed ratio of 2:1 (H2O); a mixture would have variable proportions. (2) Water's properties (liquid at room temperature, colourless, etc.) are entirely different from its components — hydrogen and oxygen are both gases at room temperature; a mixture would keep the properties of its parts. (3) Water can only be broken into its elements by a chemical reaction (electrolysis), not by physical methods; mixtures are separated physically. All three points confirm it is a compound, not a mixture.", explanation: "Fixed ratio, new properties, and need for chemical reaction all prove water is a compound." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "hard", q: "Carbon dioxide (CO2) is a compound. Which evidence best proves it is NOT a mixture of carbon and oxygen?", options: ["It contains carbon and oxygen atoms", "It always has exactly two oxygen atoms for every one carbon atom and has properties different from either element", "It can be detected with a limewater test", "It is a gas at room temperature"], answer: 1, explanation: "A compound has a fixed ratio of atoms and distinct properties different from its elements. CO2 always has a 1:2 C:O ratio and is a gas with different properties from solid carbon and oxygen gas — proof it is a compound, not a mixture." }
          ]
